# Volume V — Declaration of Meditation

### Receiving, Understanding, and Living the Word

## Preamble

Before we interpret,
we listen.

Before we conclude,
we ask.

Before we apply,
we reflect.

Scripture is not merely
a record of what once happened.

It is testimony received through history
and carried from one generation
to another.

To read Scripture
is not merely to gather information.

It is to stand before a truth
that asks to be heard,

understood,

remembered,

and lived.

Meditation begins
when reading refuses to end
with information.

## Article I — Scripture Comes Before Us

Scripture does not begin with us.

Its words were spoken
before our questions were formed.

We do not create its meaning.

We receive a text shaped by language,

history,

memory,

and faith.

We approach Scripture
as recipients,

not owners.

We do not force it
to confirm what we already believe.

We allow it
to challenge what we assume.

## Article II — We Listen Before We Apply

Every passage was spoken
within a time,

a place,

a language,

and a people.

We first ask:

What does the text say?

What did it mean
to those who first received it?

What happened before?

What follows afterward?

Context does not imprison Scripture
in the past.

It allows us to hear
what was actually said
before asking what it says to us now.

## Article III — Scripture Is Many Texts and One Story

Scripture is law and poetry,

history and prophecy,

wisdom and lament,

Gospel and testimony.

Each text must be read
according to what it is.

Yet these writings
do not remain isolated.

One promise remembers another.

One image opens into another.

The Scriptures speak
across generations
as one unfolding story.

## Article IV — We Read in the Light of Christ

The Scriptures reveal God's work
through covenant,

deliverance,

judgment,

mercy,

exile,

return,

and promise.

What was revealed in many forms
was brought into focus
in Jesus Christ.

The Gospel does not erase
what came before it.

It fulfils it.

The cross and resurrection
do not turn the earlier Scriptures
into hidden codes.

They reveal the direction
toward which the story has moved.

We therefore read
from after the resurrection,

with greater knowledge
and greater responsibility.

## Article V — Meditation Is Faithful Attention

Meditation is not
adding our thoughts to Scripture.

It is allowing Scripture
to enter our thoughts,

our memory,

our judgment,

and our desires.

Interpretation asks:

> What does this text mean?

Meditation continues:

> What does this truth reveal?

> What does it confront?

> How must it change the way I live?

Meditation begins
when understanding remains with us
long enough to transform us.

## Article VI — Questions Lead Us Toward Truth

We do not ask questions
because truth does not exist.

We ask
because truth is greater
than our first understanding.

Questions are not always
the rejection of faith.

They may be
an act of reverence.

We choose careful questions
over premature conclusions.

Where Scripture is clear,
we speak clearly.

Where evidence is divided,
we remain humble.

Where we do not know,
we remain honest.

## Article VII — Study and Reflection Belong Together

Meditation without study
may mistake instinct for revelation.

Study without meditation
may examine Scripture
without ever hearing it.

We refuse this separation.

Observation comes before interpretation.

Interpretation comes before reflection.

Reflection comes before application.

Research helps us understand.

Verification tests our conclusions.

Reflection allows truth
to enter life.

None replaces the other.

## Article VIII — Meditation Becomes Witness

The Acts of the Apostles shows
how the first disciples learned
to live after the resurrection.

They waited.

They questioned.

They remembered Scripture.

They crossed boundaries.

They revised expectations.

They became witnesses.

Their journey teaches us
that revelation is not merely understood.

It is received,

tested,

embodied,

and carried forward.

Meditation does not end
within the mind.

What is faithfully received
must become a faithful life.

## Final Declaration

We will read
before we explain.

We will observe
before we interpret.

We will research
before we assert.

We will reflect
before we apply.

We will ask
before we conclude.

We will not reduce Scripture
to information.

We will not reduce meditation
to emotion.

We will not disguise
our own voice
as the voice of God.

We will receive the text
as testimony.

We will seek its meaning
within its world.

We will read its story
in the light of the cross
and resurrection.

We will allow the Word
to question us
as we question it.

We will preserve
what has been faithfully learned.

We will revise
what can no longer be sustained.

We will not claim
to possess the truth.

We will remain
within its pursuit.

We do not meditate
to make Scripture ours.

We meditate
so that our lives
may be shaped by what is true.

## Closing Principle

Scripture is not exhausted
when it has been explained.

Meditation begins
where understanding becomes reflection,

reflection becomes faithfulness,

and faithfulness becomes witness.
